    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a comparative market analysis in Brisbane real estate?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A comparative market analysis (CMA) is an estimate of your property's likely sale price based on recent sales of comparable properties in your suburb. It is prepared by an agent before you list and is not a formal valuation, but it is the primary tool used to set a realistic price guide for your campaign."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How accurate is a CMA for Brisbane inner east properties?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A well-prepared CMA using genuinely comparable recent sales in the same suburb can be accurate to within 5 to 10 percent for most inner east Brisbane homes. Accuracy depends on how similar the comparables are in size, condition, land area, and location, and on how active the local market has been in the preceding three to six months."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a CMA the same as a bank valuation?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. A CMA is an agent's market-based estimate and carries no legal weight. A bank valuation is conducted by a licensed valuer and is used by lenders to confirm the security value of a property for lending purposes. Bank valuations are often more conservative than CMAs, particularly in fast-moving markets."
      }
    }
  ]
}
